"1304–Female":"1304–Deceased","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1276–1336":"1276–1336","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","1336":"1336","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbon","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborne","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Oborne in Dorset. The placename derives from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’.","possibly from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]},{"name":"Orsburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbun","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Hoskin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osekin</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a pet form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Os-</i> (particularly <i>Osbert</i>, as well as <i>Osbern</i>, and <i>Osmund</i>) + the Flemish diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. All three personal names were current in medieval Cornwall or Devon; see   Osborne  ,   Osmond  , and   Opie   (a pet form of <i>Osbert</i>). Old English <i>Ōsbeorn</i>, <i>Ōsbeohrt</i>, and <i>Ōsmund</i> may also have contributed in a minor way to Middle English usage; Middle English   Oswald   is another possible source, but the name was very rare in the late 14th century. For the excrescent initial <i>H-</i>, compare   Herrick  ."]},{"name":"Osborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Orsborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborn","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name chiefly from Oborne in Dorset, or perhaps occasionally from Howbourne Farm in Hadlow Down, Sussex, Woburn in Bedfordshire, Woburn Park in Surrey, or Wooburn in Buckinghamshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, except Wooburn in Buckinghamshire, which is of uncertain etymology.","English (of Norman origin): perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When John Thomas Osborne was born in 1300, in England, his father, William Osborne, was 24 and his mother, Sarah Cooper, was 24. He married Mary Robson in 1320, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1377, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1300–1377":"1300–1377","1301–1360":"1301–1360","1304–Female":"1304–Surnud","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1276–1336":"1276–1336","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1304":"1304","1336":"1336","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England"},"fi":{"1300–1377":"1300–1377","1301–1360":"1301–1360","1304–Female":"1304–Kuollut","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1276–1336":"1276–1336","1276–Female":"1276–Kuollut","